The goal of this project was to increase the participation of underrepresented minorities in STEM. Despite years of effort, representation of underrepresented minorities in STEM, particularly in the Mathematical and Computer Sciences, is adamantly stagnant. One reason is the belief by the underrepresented minority groups that they can better impact society by pursuing disciplines such as Law than by pursuing STEM. We therefore injected social justice issues into STEM learning through data science. We achieved this by incorporating data science projects within a social justice context to make it apparent to underrepresented minority students, how STEM serves as a vehicle for addressing social inequities with the goal of encouraging interest and promoting persistence in STEM.
As one of the primary deliverables from this project, we sourced and curated more than 10 datasets on the following social justice topics: police killings, gun violence, domestic violence, sexual assault, COVID-19, environmental pollution, cost of college education, child abuse, and LGBTQ+ data. Our list of social justice topics, along with curated datasets, and research and guiding questions, are available on our project website (https://sites.google.com/view/dssj). More than 100 Freshman Seminar students at NC Central University, regardless of major, selected and worked on the DSSJ topics from the list provided for their required Freshman Seminar project.
From an effectiveness study of the materials piloted using a pre-post data science experience assessment, the following statistically significant key findings for student participants were found:
1)   Increase in students' data science knowledge;
2)   Greater interest in data science as a career option;
3)   Greater awareness of big data use across employment sectors; and
4)   Increased desire to become more knowledgeable about data science.
The study also included qualitative data collection from a number of sources including student focus groups, course observations, instructor interviews, and course artifact reviews.  Analyses of these data yielded the following findings:
1)   Students valued the use of CODAP as an analysis tool for data exploration;
2)   Students described the exposure to data explorations as "powerful"; and
3)   Students and faculty found the topics to be relevant and interesting.
The following additional key observations, among others, were also made:
1)   selection of social justice topics with input from students at a HBCU boosted student engagement;
2)   an interdisciplinary approach that incorporates the perspectives of other disciplines is important;
3)   identifying the right tool for the data exploration required careful attention so that the data science introduction would not put up the well-known barriers for HMC students in entering STEM and computing;
4)   for many students the word "data" is equated with "math" and triggers the same beliefs students hold about themselves as math students;
5)   beyond developing future data scientists, HBCU faculty from the humanities and social sciences raised an equally loud call for the need to develop social scientists and scholars from a wide array of fields to be engaged in data science study and discourse.

This project's work has been well-received nationally and generated a lot of interest in the education-focused data science community. As shown in the attached figure, our datasets have been cumulatively downloaded more than 1200 times. Based on the comments and requests we have received through our dissemination efforts, there is a great need to provide such curated datasets. From the usage metrics for our curated data, it is clear that providing curated datasets on social justice topics is benefiting the community. The conversion rate for our curated social justice datasets is more than 39%. In comparison, the average conversion rate in Google ads across all industries is 4.40% and in the jobs and education industry is 4.15% [Source: Bond, C. (2022). Conversion Rate Benchmarks: Find out how your conversion rate compares. https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/08/19/conversion-rate-benchmarks (accessed Oct 1, 2022)].








